# Tempo Flow — git + PR workflow

Source of truth: @docs/HARD_RULES.md §12 (git + PR rules) and §14 (owner-tag discipline).

## Never push to `master`

- All changes land through a pull request against `master`.
- Branch protection is enabled; direct pushes will be rejected.
- `master` is always deployable. If a PR would break it, fix the PR or revert.

## Branch naming

Use one of:

- `feat/T-XXXX-<short-kebab>` — new feature tied to a `TASKS.md` row
- `fix/T-XXXX-<short-kebab>` — bug fix tied to a `TASKS.md` row
- `chore/<scope>-<short-kebab>` — tooling, CI, deps, no user impact
- `docs/<scope>-<short-kebab>` — docs-only changes

`T-XXXX` matches the task ID format in `docs/TASKS.md`.

## Commits + PR titles

- Conventional Commits: `feat(scope): ...`, `fix(scope): ...`, `chore(scope): ...`.
- One logical change per PR. Stack PRs for large features.

## Opening a PR

- Run the `/pr` slash command, or run `gh pr create --base master` manually.
- The PR uses `.github/pull_request_template.md` — fill in every section.
- Link the `TASKS.md` task ID. Copy acceptance criteria verbatim.
- Attach screenshots or a short screen recording for any UI change.

## Review + merge

- Reviewer is Amit (`human-amit`) by default. A second code agent may be tagged
  `reviewer` only after human approval.
- **Code agents never merge their own PRs.** Stop after the PR is open.
- Resolve every review conversation before merge.

## Owner-tag discipline (§14)

- Only claim tasks whose owner tag matches your agent identity.
- `cursor-cloud-1` does not touch `cursor-cloud-2` work, and vice versa.
- `twin`, `pokee`, `zo`, and `human-amit` tasks are off-limits to code agents.
- Never ask a human to do work labeled for a code agent.
- Never have a code agent click a web dashboard — that is Twin's job.
